7 Candidate variables (with short explanations):

Age — People are more likely to smoke at certain ages than others

Poverty — More exposure to people who smoke around you

Marijuana — If yes, less prone to choosing cigarettes over marijuana

Hard drugs — If yes, less prone to choosing cigarettes over hard drugs

Gender — Cultural norms may make women less likely to smoke

Marital status — Less likely to smoke in consideration for their children

Therefore, say
\[
\log\left(\frac{p}{1-p}\right) = \beta_0
+ \beta_1\text{Age}
+ \beta_2\text{Poverty}
+ \beta_3\text{Marijuana}_{\text{Yes}}
+ \beta_4\text{HardDrugs}_{\text{Yes}}
+ \beta_5\text{Gender}_{\text{female}}
+ \beta_6\text{MS}_{\text{Married}}
+ \beta_7\text{MS}_{\text{Divorced}}
+ \beta_8\text{MS}_{\text{LivePartner}}
+ \beta_9\text{MS}_{\text{Separated}}
+ \beta_{10}\text{MS}_{\text{Widowed}}
\]
where \(p = P(\text{SmokeNow} = 1)\) and \(\text{MS}\) denotes MaritalStatus, with as the reference category.
We test:
\[H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \cdots = \beta_{10} = 0\]
\[H_1: \text{at least one } \beta_k \neq 0, \quad k = 1, \ldots, 10\]
First, we fit a logistic regression to these variables and proceed to model selection.
